{
  "doc_id": "38277",
  "text": "via automated and parallelized approaches and reduced use of resources. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] μBRs have achieved relevant biomass densities as well as oxygen mass transfer coefficients comparable with bench scale reactors. [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] Monitoring dissolved oxygen concentrations in μBRs in real time using optical sensors is nowadays state of the art. [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] Control over oxygen can be achieved by taking advantage of the high diffusivity and solubility of oxygen in poly(dimethylsiloxane) (PDMS). [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] In their pioneering work, Lee et al. [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] were able to control oxygen concentrations by pressurizing a PDMS membrane with air (or any other gas mixture). Demonstrating that OUR can be measured in real time will therefore further consolidate the applicability of microbioreactors, and will potentially strengthen the link to conventional stirred tank reactors for scale-up studies.",
